Records of the Institute of African American Affairs

Contents

Series I. Events Files, 1978-1992

langmaterial

English

Extent

8 Linear Feet in 8 containers.

Scope and Contents

This series contains material related to events hosted or organized by the Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) dating from 1978 to 1991 including conferences, lectures, exhibition openings, book readings, and panel discussions. Files typically contain publicity material, correspondence, notes, and budgets. Events of note include the Black Scholars Lecture Series, Black History Month celebrations, Community Lecture Series, Black Male Conference, Black Theater Forum, and Caribbean Conference. See also Series III for IAAA Director office files related to events; Series IV.B for audiovisual event recordings; and Series V. for event planning files from later years.

Arrangement

Files are arranged chronologically.

Series II. Association for Education in Journalism (AEJ), 1970-1993

langmaterial

English

Extent

7 Linear Feet in 7 containers.

Scope and Contents

In 1970, Founding IAAA Director Dr. Roscoe C. Brown Jr. and Dr. Lionel Barrow, Dean of Howard University School of Communications, created the Association for Education in Journalism Summer Internship Program for Minorities. This series includes files related to the administration of the AEJ internship program dating from 1970 to 1993. Files typically include correspondence, class arrangements, finances, forms, reports, magazines, and individual files on interns and finalists of the program.

Arrangement

Files are arranged chronologically.

Summer Internship Informational Packet, 1993

31142063585106box: 67, folder: 9 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)

Series III. Director Files, 1966-2006

langmaterial

English

Extent

22 Linear Feet in 22 containers.
579.30 Megabytes in 51 computer files.

Scope and Contents

This series contains paper and computer files generated by past Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) Directors including Founding Director Roscoe C. Brown Jr. (served from 1969 to 1977), Acting Director Edward M. Carroll (served from 1977 to 1979), Earl S. Davis (served 1979 to 1994) and Manthia Diawara (1992-2018). Files include advisory group minutes; IAAA Director and staff correspondence; conference packets and notes; IAAA histories and annual reports; Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Program material; and Black Scholars Lecture Series speaker information. Articles and scholarly journals found in files throughout this series that pre-date the IAAA were likely accumulated for subject or research files by the Directors.

This series also contains project files from 1979 to 1987 related to multiple scholarly monographs published by IAAA. The original monograph was produced by a group of Black scholars to commemorate IAAA's 10th anniversary in 1979. After its successful release, additional monographs were published in later years.

Series IV. Audiovisual Recordings, 1963-2007

langmaterial

English,English

Extent

50 Linear Feet in 44 record cartons, 3 card boxes, 2 cassette boxes, and 4 flat boxes.
627 sound tape reels
251 audiocassettes
267 videocassettes (vhs)
32 videocassettes (betacam)
153 videocassettes (u-matic)
4 videocassettes (dvcam)
54 videocassettes (minidv)
1 videocassettes (hi8)

Scope and Contents

This series contains audiovisual recordings dating from 1963 to 2007 for Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) events, radio shows, conferences, and musical performances.

Arrangement

The series is arranged into three subseries: IV.A. The Soul of Reason Audio Recordings; Subseries IV.B. Events Recordings; and Subseries IV.C. Pre-Institute Recordings. Material within each subseries is arranged chronologically.

Subseries IV.A. The Soul of Reason Audio Recordings, 1971-1978

langmaterial

English

Extent

13 Linear Feet in 13 record cartons.
266 sound tape reels

Scope and Contents

This sub-series contains 266 audio recordings of The Soul of Reason radio show for episodes which aired between 1971 and 1978. These recordings represents a portion of the shows that aired from 1971 to 1986. Interviewees for the show included politicians, medical professionals, educators, professional athletes, writers, performers, and contemporary visual artists who discussed issues affecting the Black and Puerto Rican communities, and economically-deprived neighborhoods of New York City. Regularly discussed topics were the American Bicentennial, the creation of the Gateway National Recreation Area, the relocation of the New York Public Library's Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture, and the effects of New York City's fiscal crisis on education, employment, and healthcare for these communities. Repeat guests included Vice Chairman of the Democratic National Committee Basil Paterson; President of the New York Urban Coalition Arthur Barnes; Editor for Black Sports Magazine Allan Barron; Editor-at-Large for Black Enterprise magazine Pat Patterson; jazz pianist Mary Lou Williams; authors Nathan Huggins and John O. Killens; and doctors John Holloman, June Christmas, and Ivory Carr.

Arrangement

The Soul of Reason audio recordings are arranged chronologically by date of broadcast.

Historical Note

The Soul of Reason (SoR) was a half-hour, talk-show format radio show that aired from 1971-1986 as a result of a collaboration between the commercial radio station WNBC and New York University's station WNYU. The host of the program, Dr. Roscoe C. Brown, Jr. was also the Director of the Institute of Afro-American Affairs (IAAA) at NYU at the time. The show's mission was to be "a showcase for Black scholarship….to examine the foundations of African-American thought from a variety of areas," according to founding documents for the show. During each episode, Brown conducted an informal, back and forth dialogue with a variety of professionals, mainly from the New York City area, who spoke personally to the unique challenges of the Black experience. These shows initially aired at 10pm and 12am on WNBC and rebroadcast a few weeks later on WNYU.

Williams, Charles T. "Chuck" -- Vice President of the Schenley Affiliated Brands Corporation and Member of the Board for the Jackie Robinson Foundation, 1977-10-06

31142062747269box: 40, folder: 25 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)
langmaterial
English
Scope and Contents

Dr. Roscoe C. Brown, Jr. and Charles T. "Chuck" Williams discuss how Jackie Robinson -- a man they both knew well -- created opportunities for Black athletes, as well as fought for social, economic, and political justice for all Americans. However, a cause of particular interest to Robinson was providing educational and recreational opportunities for economically-deprived Black children. As a result, the Jackie Robinson Foundation identified its objective as providing support for Black children through an internship program.

Subseries IV.B. Events Recordings, 1970-2007

langmaterial

English

Extent

34.50 Linear Feet in 29 record cartons, 2 cassette boxes, 1 card box, and 4 flat boxes.
267 videocassettes (vhs)
251 audiocassettes
168 sound tape reels
153 videocassettes (u-matic)
54 videocassettes (minidv)
32 videocassettes (betacam)
4 videocassettes (dvcam)
1 videocassettes (hi8)

Scope and Contents

This subseries contains audio and video recordings of programs, panels, readings, lectures, and music performances related to the Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) dating from 1970 to 2007. This subseries includes speakers for the Black Genius Series including Angela Davis, Anna Deavere Smith, Joycelyn Elders, Stanley Crouch, and Walter Mosley. Other events include panel discussions and events for the Yari Yari: Black Women Writers and the Future Conferences; and recorded sessions from the 1982 Black Male Conferences; Birth of Black Cinema Symposium; and Slave Routes: The Long Memory Symposium. This subseries also contains footage from a circa 2000 Africa trip with Manthia Diawara and Danny Glover for the documentary, Diaspora Conversations from Goree to Dogon. See Series I and V for paper and electronic files containing event planning and publicity material.

Arrangement

Recordings are arranged in chronological order, followed by undated material.

Processing Information

Select creator-supplied titles containing racist language were identified in this subseries, but have been retained to convey important contextual information regarding time and place in which the recordings and titles were created.

Subseries IV.C. Pre-Institute Recordings, 1963-1968

Extent

9 Linear Feet in 9 record cartons.
193 sound tape reels

Scope and Contents

This subseries contains audio recordings created prior to the formation of the Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) in 1969. This subseries includes audio recordings of the May 1965 Teach-In at NYU, featuring IAAA Founding Director Dr. Roscoe C. Brown Jr.

This subseries also includes the 1963 to 1967 audio recordings from The Urban League Presents, a recurring radio show produced by the Communication Arts Group of New York University for the Urban League of Greater New York. Episode content reflects this organization's mission as a nonpartisan historic civil rights organization that advocates on behalf of economic and social justice for African Americans and against racial discrimination in the United States. These recordings were broadcast initially on other stations and rebroadcast on WNYU. Earlier episodes dating from 1959 to 1962 are available in the University Archives Audiovisual Collection (AV).

Processing Information

Select creator-supplied titles containing ableist language were identified in this subseries, but have been retained to convey important contextual information regarding time and place in which the recordings and titles were created.

Series V. Administrative Files, 1979, 1986-20041993-1999

Extent

6 Linear Feet in 13 manuscript boxes and 1 half manuscript box.
21.27 Gigabytes in 1,534 computer files.

Scope and Contents

This series includes computer and paper files created and collected by the Institute of African American Affairs (IAAA) which relate to the general administration of the organization, including press releases and promotional material; individual files for Artists and Scholars-in-Residence; project files for Sports Matters and Basketball Project events; planning for film screenings and book signings; and Black Genius work files which relate to the publishing of the book and lecture series. Typically planning files contain contact and mailing lists; correspondence; event photographs; portraits of speakers and celebrities; and schedules. Some computer files also contain audio and video recordings from panel discussions, art openings, and conferences, a short movie, and music recordings.

Work files for the IAAA publication Black Renaissance Noire are in this series, dating from 1992 to 2004. Files include copies of essays, papers, poems, and reviews that were included in various issues.

Arrangement

This series has not been arranged by an archivist. The materials are arranged in the order in which they were received from the donor.

Processing Information

Select creator-supplied titles containing racist language were identified in this series, but have been retained to convey important contextual information regarding time and place in which the documents and titles were created.
